Source: The New York Times, Tue 8 May 2001 [edited
<http://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/08/nyregion/08NILE.html>

Two Dead Crows in New Jersey Herald the Re-emergence of WNV in 2001
-------------------------------------------------------------------
New Jersey health officials have identified 2 crows infected with West Nile
virus (WNV) in what is believed to be the first occurrence [confirmation
of the disease [infection this season in the New York metropolitan region.
The infected crows were among 22 dead birds found in two-thirds of the
state's counties, said a spokesman for the state Department of Health and
Senior Services in Trenton.
One of the infected crows was found on 30 April 2001 at Upper Saddle River,
in Bergen County, in the northern part of the state. The other was found on
2 May 2001 at Edison, in Middlesex County, in the central part of the state.
Since 1999, when the virus was detected for the first time in the Western
Hemisphere, in New York, states in the region have increased their
surveillance for the mosquitoes that pass the infection to birds and
humans. Last year in New Jersey there were 6 cases in humans, resulting in
one death. Bob Kent, director of the state office of Mosquito Control
Coordination, said most counties in New Jersey had been on the alert since
March, conducting surveillance of adult mosquitoes and their larvae and
trying to eliminate areas of standing water where mosquitoes might breed.
Testing dead birds has been adopted as the best early-warning system for
detecting the virus in the area, he said. The positive results for the 2
crows will lead Middlesex and Bergen Counties to intensify their
surveillance of the adult mosquito population. Only if that effort turns up
more infected mosquitoes, officials said, will they consider local
spraying. The strategy was controversial last year.
[Byline: Ronald Smothers
